# bib2cv

A lightweight Python package that converts BibTeX publications into LaTeX CV entries (`\item ...`), optimized for an academic astronomy CV workflow.

## Installation

```bash
pip install -e .
```

## Quick Start

```bash
# Basic usage — prints LaTeX \item entries to stdout
bib2cv pubs.bib

# Write to file
bib2cv pubs.bib -o output.tex

# With per-entry overrides (accepted/submitted status, journal)
bib2cv pubs.bib --overrides overrides.json
```

## Features

- **Author formatting**: `Last F.` / `Last F.~M.` style with non-breaking spaces
- **Author bolding**: Automatically bolds your name (default: `Li, Jiaxuan`)
- **Smart truncation**: When your position exceeds the threshold (default 5), shows first 4 authors + `et al. (including \textbf{Your Name})`
- **Title links**: Wraps titles in `\href{}{}` using ADS URL > DOI > arXiv precedence
- **Journal resolution**: Maps ADS BibTeX macros (`\apj`, `\apjl`, `\mnras`, ...) to CV-style abbreviations
- **Status detection**: Automatically detects published / accepted / arXiv-only papers
- **Reverse chronological sorting** by year, month, then title

## Per-Entry Overrides

Create a JSON file to override status or journal for specific entries:

```json
{
    "2025arXiv250408032M": {
        "status": "accepted",
        "journal": "ApJL"
    },
    "2025arXiv250100001X": {
        "status": "submitted",
        "journal": "MNRAS"
    }
}
```

Supported `status` values: `"published"`, `"accepted"`, `"submitted"`, `"arxiv"`, `"in prep"`.

### Status rendering

| Status      | Has journal? | Output example                                    |
|-------------|-------------|---------------------------------------------------|
| `published` | yes         | `\textit{ApJL} 998, L24 (2026).`                 |
| `accepted`  | yes         | `\textit{ApJL} accepted.`                         |
| `submitted` | yes         | `\textit{ApJL} submitted.`                        |
| `arxiv`     | no          | `arXiv:2501.00001.`                               |
| `arxiv`     | yes (override) | `\textit{ApJL} submitted, arXiv:2501.00001.`  |

## CLI Options

```
bib2cv INPUT.bib [-o OUTPUT] [--author "Last, First"] [--overrides FILE] [--max-position N] [--no-sort]
```

| Flag             | Default          | Description                                    |
|------------------|------------------|------------------------------------------------|
| `--author`       | `Li, Jiaxuan`    | Name to bold, in `Last, First` format          |
| `--overrides`    | —                | JSON file for per-entry status/journal overrides|
| `--max-position` | `5`              | Author position threshold for truncation       |
| `--no-sort`      | off              | Disable reverse-chronological sorting          |
| `-o`             | stdout           | Output file path                               |

## Python API

```python
from bib2cv import parse_bibfile, format_entries
from bib2cv.formatter import FormatterConfig

entries = parse_bibfile("pubs.bib")
cfg = FormatterConfig(
    owner_last="Li",
    owner_first="Jiaxuan",
    overrides={"2025arXiv250408032M": {"status": "accepted", "journal": "ApJL"}},
)
print(format_entries(entries, cfg))
```

## Example Output

```latex
\item Ma Y., Greene J.~E., Setton D.~J., Goulding A.~D. et al. (including \textbf{Li J.}), \href{...}{Counting Little Red Dots...}, \textit{ApJ} 1000, 59 (2026).

\item \textbf{Li J.}, Greene J.~E., Danieli S., Carlsten S.~G., Geha M., \href{...}{A Possible ``Too-Many-Satellites'' Problem...}, \textit{ApJL} 998, L24 (2026).

\item Cheng S., \textbf{Li J.}, Yang E., \href{...}{Discovery of a Dwarf Planet Candidate...}, \textit{ApJL} 998, L6 (2026).
```

## Running Tests

```bash
pip install -e ".[test]"
python -m pytest tests/ -v
```

